This should serve as the final design baseline before implementation.

1) Final API Decisions
ExceptionLogger — keep all 3 methods
We decided to keep:

log()
log_many()
log_dataframe()

Why
Because ExceptionLogger supports three legitimate input shapes:

single technical / validation exception → log()
multiple violations for one logical record → log_many()
table-wide Spark validation failures in a DataFrame → log_dataframe()


EventLogger — keep single + optional bulk DataFrame
We decided to keep:

log()
log_dataframe() (only if bulk event logging is needed)

And:

do not add log_many() to EventLogger

Why
Because the main event use cases are:

one event at a time
or bulk events via DataFrame if needed

A separate log_many() for events was judged unnecessary.

Rename EventLogger.log_event() to log()
We decided to standardize the single-record event method name:

EventLogger.log_event() → EventLogger.log()

Why
To make method naming consistent with ExceptionLogger.log().

2) Method Signature / Parameter Changes

2.1 Standardize on variable_name
We decided that the public API should use:

variable_name

instead of:

field

Applies to

ExceptionLogger.log()
ExceptionLogger.log_many() / Violation
ExceptionLogger.log_dataframe()
docs/examples/tests

Why
The team already uses variable_name, so we align with established terminology.

2.2 Keep variable_name_column in log_dataframe()
We decided to keep:

variable_name
variable_name_column

in log_dataframe()
Why
They represent two different valid validation output shapes:
A. Constant variable_name
For one-field-at-a-time validation:

null check on i_mode
range check on i_age

B. variable_name_column
For normalized/generic validation outputs where one failure DataFrame contains failures for different variables:

person_nbr null
i_mode null
i_id null

Important naming decision
We decided not to rename variable_name_column to variable_column_names.
Why
variable_name_column is more accurate:

the parameter is the name of one DataFrame column
that DataFrame column contains variable names


2.3 response_id vs response_id_column
We decided that in log_dataframe() we will keep only:

response_id_column

and not keep constant response_id in log_dataframe().
Why
In table/bulk validation use cases, response_id is naturally row-specific, not constant.
This applies to both:

one-variable-at-a-time validations
normalized multi-variable validations

Final rule

log() / log_many() → response_id = actual value
log_dataframe() → response_id_column = name of DataFrame column containing response IDs


2.4 observed vs observed_column
We decided that in log_dataframe() we will keep only:

observed_column

and not keep constant observed in log_dataframe().
Why
For DataFrame/table validation, observed values are row-specific and should come from the DataFrame.
Final rule

log() / log_many() → observed = actual observed value
log_dataframe() → observed_column = name of DataFrame column containing observed values


2.5 expected stays constant in log_dataframe()
We decided to keep:

expected

as a constant in log_dataframe()
and not add / use:

expected_column (for now)

Why
For most validation rules, expected is naturally constant across the whole validation call:

"non-null"
"0..120"
"Online | Phone | Visit"
"iso-8601"

Adding expected_column now would make common validations unnecessarily more complex.

2.6 rule vs rule_name stays as-is
We decided to keep the distinction:

ExceptionLogger → rule
EventLogger → rule_name

Why
They are semantically different:

rule = registry-backed validation rule key
rule_name = free-text event/business rule name

This is an intentional difference and should be documented clearly.

2.7 log_many() simplified to one logical record
We decided to simplify ExceptionLogger.log_many() so that:

response_id is scalar only
remove support for response_id as a list

Final shape
log_many() is now explicitly:

multiple violations for one logical record / one shared response_id

Why
If failures span many response IDs, that is a log_dataframe() use case.

2.8 EventLogger log_dataframe() should support message and message_column
We decided for EventLogger.log_dataframe() to keep both:

message
message_column

with mutual exclusivity.
Why
Both are valid bulk event patterns:
A. message
When every row represents the same event message
B. message_column
When each row has its own event message
Decision
We will not overload message to sometimes mean a literal and sometimes mean a DataFrame column selector.
That would be too confusing.

2.9 EventLogger log_dataframe() should use response_id_column
For EventLogger bulk logging, we decided to use:

response_id_column

rather than constant response_id
Why
Bulk event rows are also table/dataframe-driven and should use row-level identity from a column.

2.10 EventLogger may also support variable_name / variable_name_column
We agreed that if EventLogger.log_dataframe() is kept, it may also support:

variable_name
variable_name_column

when needed
Why
Some bulk event rows may all relate to one variable, while others may be generic event rows spanning multiple variables.

3) Schema / Table Changes
3.1 Add expected and observed columns to the exceptions log table
We decided to add structured columns to the exceptions table/schema:

expected
observed

Why
Right now these values are mostly embedded in the message.
Adding them as columns makes the exceptions table more queryable and more useful analytically.
Expected representation
These should likely be stored as nullable strings.

3.2 Update ExceptionLogger._SCHEMA
Because of the above, ExceptionLogger._SCHEMA must be updated to include:

expected
observed

And record assembly must populate them.

3.3 Table migration / DDL change required
Because the schema changes affect the target Delta table, we will need:

migration / DDL update for the exceptions table

This is not just a Python change
It must be reflected in the physical target table too.

4) Object Model Changes
4.1 Add message to Violation
We decided to use Option 2 for Violation:
Add optional:

message

New conceptual shape
Violation will contain:

rule
variable_name
expected
observed
message (optional)

Why
Different violations in one batch may need different human-readable messages.
So message belongs on each violation, not as one shared log_many() parameter.

5) Behavioral Changes
5.1 Framework-managed observation_id everywhere
We decided to keep observation_id:

always auto-generated
not caller-supplied publicly

Applies especially to EventLogger
We decided to remove the public override behavior from EventLogger.log() for:

observation_id

Why
This keeps the API simpler and consistent across both loggers.

5.2 Framework-managed timestamps everywhere
We decided to keep timestamps:

always auto-generated by the logger
not caller-supplied publicly

Applies especially to EventLogger
We decided to remove the public override behavior from EventLogger.log() for:

created_timestamp_utc

Why
Consistent behavior across both loggers and less API clutter.

5.3 Keep using uuid.uuid4() for now (not UUIDv7)
We decided to stick with uuid.uuid4() for now rather than moving to UUIDv7.
Why

uuid.uuid7() is documented in the Python 3.14 standard library docs, so it should not be assumed available in older Python environments. [docs.python.org]
Databricks documentation does not suggest that uuid6 / uuid-utils are universally preinstalled defaults, so introducing UUIDv7 via third-party package would require explicit dependency management. [docs.databricks.com], [docs.databricks.com], [learn.microsoft.com]

Final decision

keep uuid.uuid4() now
revisit UUIDv7 later only if there is a strong operational reason


